AGI -&nbsp; On May 13, 1981 it is said that in St. Peter's Square there was a miracle. It is remembered by a stone arranged > among the sampietrini. On that date - the day of the first apparition of Our Lady to the three shepherds of Fatima > (Portugal) - and precisely at that point, the Turkish Mehemet Ali Ağca of the extreme right group of the Grigi Wolves, with his weapon Browning HP caliber 9 shot Pope Karol Wojtyla, today Saint John Paul II.
The killer (subito arrested) wanted to hit him at the head> but the story went differently. The Polish pontiff was wounded in one hand and intestine.
“It was a maternal hand that led the trajectory of the bullet,” said the holy father. According to him, Mary had protected him, the one to whom she had dedicated herself and also her apostolic motto: Totus tuus, all yours. Twelve months later, on May 13, 1982 John Paul II wanted to hold that saving hand. He went to Portugal on a visit to the Shrine of Fatima > and delivered one of the ogives that should have killed him: since then the bullet is set in the crown of the statue of the Virgin.> By the will of Benedict XVI, the memory of that miracle is kept in the marble plate on the floor of St. Peter's Square, with engraved the papal coat of arms of Wojtyla and in Roman numerals the date of the attack. What about Ağca? In 2010 he returned free.
After years of investigation of the judiciary, the identity of the alleged mandate has not yet been established, of those who wanted to die the pope “enemy of communism”. So many scenarios, no one confirmed. Over time and several times the terrorist has fantasized ever different plots, coming to proclaim itself “new messiah”. The Turkish has raised doubts, launched accusations and uncertainties.
